**********************************************************************************
*****THIS KCP IS INTENDED TO MODEL A COMMERIAL THIN IN BIOGROUPS 4, 5, AND 6******
*******ASSOCIATED WITH DRY, WARM DRY, and SOME MOIST FOREST TYPES*****************
***************INCLUDES LanFin KCP TO COMPUTE ECON COSTS**************************
****************************SOUTH UMATILLA****************************************
**********************************************************************************

*****************************************************************************************************
*This sets the species preference for Biogroups 4, 5, and 6.  This preference cuts the 
*CP first and retains GF.  This also sets the defect at 10-percent (Kone Hancock, 2/1/2019)
*and the sawtimber minimum specifications as defined by the Umatilla NF Sale Prep Guide ver
*4/2017 (Pg. 40). The Volume keyword does not specify log length for those 8 (All other spp.)
*and 16 (CP) ft that would be associated with eastside forests in the Blue Mtns of SE WA 
*and East. OR. The volume keyword is set to use the FVS Method volume equation code 2 (i.e. 
*Region 6 eastside taper equations previously in FVS).
*
*This also simulates a prescribed fire following the thinning treatment in the 2nd year following
*the thinning treatment.  D.Justice, Umatilla NF. Jan. 2020.
*****************************************************************************************************

SpecPref           0     Parms(PP, -100.)
SpecPref           0     Parms(WB, -90.0)
SpecPref           0     Parms(WP, -80.0)
SpecPref           0     Parms(WL, -70.0)
SpecPref           0     Parms(DF, -60.0)
SpecPref           0     Parms(ES, -50.0)
SpecPref           0     Parms(AF, -40.0)
SpecPref           0     Parms(LP, -30.0)
SpecPref           0     Parms(WJ, -20.0)
SpecPref           0     Parms(GF, -10.0)

****************************************************************************************************
*The following performs a thin for stands classified as Biogroups 4, 5, and 6.  This thins  
*stands that are >=55 percent of max sdi down to 30 percent max by performing a thin from below 0.1
*to 20.9-inches according to species preference above.  If <55 percent of max sdi a thin is performed
*to 25-percent of max and conducts a prescribed fire treatment in the second year following the 
*the thinning treatment.
*
*ThinSDI Arguments: ResSDI, CutEff, Species, SmDBH, LgDBH, CutCtrl.
*
*The Parms portion of the ThinSDI uses the following arguments regarding the amount of residual, 
*cutting efficiency, species, smallest dia, largest dia, and cutting control. The cutting control
*is set to a value of 1 which invokes a thin from below.
*
*The Moisture keyword modifies the fuel moisture for the prescribed fire that follows.  The SimFire
*keyword is set to a windspeed of 8-mph, with a moisture of moist (argument 3), temp 70
*degrees F., mortality based upon FFE-FVS (argument code 1), 60-percent of the stand burned, 
*and the season set to Fall (argument code 4). The MOISTURE modifier modifies the moisture parameters
*from FFE-FVS to estimate local conditions. 
****************************************************************************************************

****************************************************************************************************
*The inventory year is set to 2020 in order to bring stands to a current year for modeling
*purposes.  The numcycle is set to 5 to capture the prescribed fire treatment.
****************************************************************************************************

InvYear         2020
NumCycle          1.

IF
BSDIMAX ge    55. AND YEAR EQ 2020
Then
ThinSDI           0     Parms(BSDIMAX*.30, 0.9, All, 0.1, 20.9, 1)
ENDIF

*Reports a potential fire, fuels, burn, mortality, and econ.

DataBase
Potfire            2
FuelsOut           2
BurnRept           2
MortRept           2 
ECONRPTS           2
End

Defect             0       All         0
        .1        .1        .1        .1        .1        .1        .1        .1

BFVolume           0        PP        9.        6.        1.        0.         2
Volume             0        PP        9.        6.        1.        0.         2
BFVolume           0        AF        7.        5.        1.        0.         2
Volume             0        AF        7.        5.        1.        0.         2
BFVolume           0        LP        7.        5.        1.        0.         2
Volume             0        LP        7.        5.        1.        0.         2
BFVolume           0        WL        7.        5.        1.        0.         2
Volume             0        WL        7.        5.        1.        0.         2
BFVolume           0        DF        7.        5.        1.        0.         2
Volume             0        DF        7.        5.        1.        0.         2
BFVolume           0        GF        7.        5.        1.        0.         2
Volume             0        GF        7.        5.        1.        0.         2
BFVolume           0        ES        7.        5.        1.        0.         2
Volume             0        ES        7.        5.        1.        0.         2
BFVolume           0        OS        7.        5.        1.        0.         2
Volume             0        OS        7.        5.        1.        0.         2

